ided by almanacs, public lectures, and demonstrations, along with the financial encouragement of early scientific societies, generated an enthusiasm for the application of science and technology to civic, commercial, and domestic improvements. Not only that: Americans were excited, awed, and intrigued with the practicality of inventions. Bringing together science and wonder, Susan Branson charts how everything from mechanical clocks to steam engines informed the creation and expansion of the American nation. From the Exhibition of the Industry of All Nations to the fate of the Amistad captives, Scientific Americans shows how the promotion and celebration of discoveries, inventions, and technologies articulated Americans' earliest ambitions, as well as prejudices, throughout the First American Century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSciencexSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencexSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory Of Technology. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aPerpetual motion machines in America, Phrenology, Centennial Exhibition, Science and Technology in American Culture, The Exhibition of the Industry of All Nations, History of American Air balloon.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176092140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501760921423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501760921/original  a978-3-